definitions.definition: ( law , Old English law ) To make a tender of; to offer or tender .
( followed by a to-infinitive ) To be likely , or probable to do something, or to have a certain habit or leaning . [from mid-14th c.]
examples: They tend to go out on Saturdays.
It tends to snow here in winter.
I was tending to get up later and later after the breakup.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To contribute to or toward some outcome.

main_definition: ( law , Old English law ) To make a tender of; to offer or tender .
secondary_definitions: ( followed by a to-infinitive ) To be likely , or probable to do something, or to have a certain habit or leaning . [from mid-14th c.]
( intransitive ) To contribute to or toward some outcome.

definitions.definition: ( with to ) To look after (e.g. an ill person.) [from early 14th c.]
examples: We need to tend to the garden, which has become a mess.

definitions.definition: To accompany as an assistant or protector; to care for the wants of; to look after; to watch; to guard.
To wait (upon), as attendants or servants; to serve ; to attend .
( obsolete ) To be attentive to; to note carefully; to attend to.
( transitive , nautical ) To manage (an anchored vessel) when the tide turns, to prevent it from entangling the cable when swinging.

definitions.definition: To kindle ; ignite ; set on fire ; light ; inflame ; burn .

main_definition: ( transitive , now chiefly dialectal ) To kindle ; ignite ; set on fire ; light ; inflame ; burn .
